SMALLPOX, HUMAN REMAINS, LIKELIHOOD: REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
============================================================
Date: Tue, 4 Mar 97 13:53:30 +0200
From: E. Vardas <VARDAS@niv.ac.za>
The National Institute for Virology and Reitfontein Infectious Diseases
Hospital in Johannesburg are facing a situation of some political and
virological concern. Unilateral decisions have been taken by some government
officials to allow low income housing projects to begin construction on the
grounds of Reitfontein hospital. The issues here are not to prevent
residential development, but rather to ensure the safety of the residents,
builders and other individuals exposed to the site, now and in the future.
To put the above statements into context, I can refer your readers to a
"Commentary" (which should be there by end of the day!) on our home page,
http://www.healthlink.org.za/niv/. In summary, the site intended for the low
cost housing is on the site of a smallpox cemetery. The last "smallpox"
burials on this land occurred in the 1950's. The land presently does not
have access to amenities such as electricity, sewage and water supplies.
These must be established before any residential development can occur. The
possibility that bodies of smallpox patients may be exhumed in the course of
this development is unfortunately very real since the records of burial
sites were not well kept. Smallpox immunisation is unavailable and if viable
smallpox is released into the non-immune population of Johannesburg (? the
world) we have a disaster on our hands. Perhaps the risks are small or
negligible, and we should not worry about this at all. I'd be interested to
know what you and your readers think.
---
Eftyhia Vardas
National Institute for Virology and
Department of Virology
University of the Witwatersrand
Johannesburg
South Africa
http://www.healthlink.org.za/niv/
TEL: 27(011) 8829910
