[This question, and ones just like it, are asked all the time. The mere
mention of smallpox is enough to make any of us dyspeptic. Although the
logistics of the question differ, the answer is usually the same. However,
for a definitive opinion, we turned to Professor Frank Fenner, John Curtin
School of Medical Research, Australia National University, Canberra, the
world authority on smallpox and Chair of the WHO committee that is overseeing
the final demise of smallpox (variola major) virus. What follows is Dr.
Fenner's very prompt and generous reply (unmoderated because, while I have a
bit of nerve, I ain't stoopid. -- Mod CHC]
"I think the risks associated with the remains of smallpox patients buried
over 40 years ago are vanishingly remote. Smallpox virus was reasonably heat-
resistant (as viruses go), but the longest known survival (by about 12 years)
was the 13 years recorded for some scabs stored at room temperature in a
Dutch laboratory. This was in scabs. I assume that all the flesh on the
bodies of patients buried some 40 years ago would have gone long ago, and the
bones would certainly not harbour the virus.
Two other points:
1. Keith Dumbell, the world's greatest authority on smallpox virus, lives
in Somerset, Cape West, South Africa. His telephone number is 27 24 554 695.
2. WHO still holds some stocks of smallpox vaccine for use in emergencies.
If the "impossible" happened, vaccine should be available from Geneva
overnight."
